President Cyril Ramaphosa addresses a press conference after the G20 Compact with Africa conference at the Chancellery. AFP/Pool JOHANNESBURG - Africa is forging a new path towards self-reliance. That is the message in President Cyril Ramaphosa’s weekly newsletter. Despite rife poverty, poor living conditions and limping national health systems that continue to batter a number of African countries. Ramaphosa says the continent managed the pandemic effectively since the first COVID-19 case in Africa was reported two years ago. READ: Ramaphosa to speak on state of a 'troubled' nation He says when decisive leadership was called for, African leaders stepped up, showing the capabilities that exist across our continent to deal with emergencies of such scale. However, he says for Africa to play a full and equal role in global affairs, it must first attend to the developmental challenges of the continent's people. Ramaphosa says Africa has however found a new voice through this experience. Building a better Africa and a better world is the cornerstone of South Africa’s foreign policy. For Africa to play a full and equal role in global affairs, we must first attend to the developmental challenges of the people of Africa. https://t.co/U4Ud6buzKL pic.twitter.com/Mmow5gtx4b